inder that the Second World War and the Cold War were a clash of cultures, not just ideologies, and asks how far intellectuals should involve themselves in politics, at a time when Mead's example is cited for and against experts' involvement in Iraq and Afghanistan.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAnthropologyxGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aCold WarxInfluence. 0aCultural relativism. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xInfluence. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Social Scientists & Psychologists.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030018785440uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030018970440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300189704423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300189704/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY